{{Infobox scientist |name = Catherine Forster |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = |birth_place = |residence = |nationality = American |death_date = |death_place = |field = [[paleontology]] |work_institution = [[George Washington University]] |alma_mater = [[University of Pennsylvania]] |doctoral_advisor = |doctoral_students = |known_for = dinosaur-bird evolution theories |prizes = |religion = |footnotes = }}
'''Catherine Ann Forster''' is an American [[paleontology|paleontologist]], [[taxonomy (biology)|taxonomist]] and expert in [[ornithopod]] evolution and ''[[Triceratops]]'' taxonomy.<ref>{{cite book| last = Farlow| first = James O.|author2= M. K. Brett-Surmann| title = The Complete Dinosaur| publisher = Indiana University Press| year = 1999| location = Bloomington, Indiana| pages = 16| isbn = 0-253-21313-4}}</ref> She is a Professor in the Geological Sciences Program and the Department of Biological Sciences at George Washington University. She obtained a B.A. and B.S. from the University of Minnesota in 1982, followed by an M.Sc. in 1985 and a Ph.D. in 1990 from the University of Pennsylvania. She then completed post-doctoral work at the University of Chicago between 1990 and 1994 in their department of Organismal Biology <ref>{{cite web |title=Columbian College of Arts and Sciences: Catherine Forster |url=https://biology.columbian.gwu.edu/catherine-forster |website=George Washington University |accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref>. She is known in part for unique bird fossils she and her colleagues have found and described from Madagascar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/mar/18/news/mn-30078|title=Fossil Discovery Bolsters Birds' Link to Dinosaurs|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nsf.gov/news/news_summ.jsp?cntn_id=102874|title=nsf.gov - National Science Foundation (NSF) News - New Sickle-Clawed Fossil From Madagascar Links Birds and Dinosaurs - US National Science Foundation (NSF)|work=nsf.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-03-18/news/9803180190_1_dinosaur-like-new-bird-species-catherine-forster|title=Unique `Dino-bird' Fossil Found In Africa|work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>
