'''Deerfoot-Bad Meat''' or  '''Api-kai-eeS''' (meaning "scabby dried meat" or "bad meat," born 1864, Blackfoot Indian Reserve, [[Alberta]], Canada - died 1897 [[Calgary]], Alberta, Canada)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/api_kai_ees_12E.html|title=Biography – API-KAI-EES – Volume XII (1891-1900) – Dictionary of Canadian Biography|access-date=2018-04-02}}</ref> was a famous [[Siksika Nation|Siksika]] [[Running|runner]] from [[Western Canada]] whose most noted achievement was winning the 1886 Calgary Star-Rink Endurance Race.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wayward-west-episode-1-deerfoot-api-kai-ees-1.4183603|title=How the legend of Deerfoot rallied Calgary — and ruined the man|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
[[File:Deerfoot Blackfoot 1880s.jpg|thumb|Deerfoot - Bad Meat (Appi-Ka-ees) c.1880 courtesy Glenbow Archives<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glenbow.org/exhibitions/online/libhtm/deerft.htm|title=Appi-Ka-ees|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>]]

== Biography ==
Deerfoot-Bad Meat was born ''c.''1864 on the Blackfoot Indian Reserve on the Western Canadian plains. The son of Nato-West-Sitsi (Medicine Fire) and nephew of Big [[Crowfoot|Chief Crowfoot]]. Deerfoot-Bad Meat followed the Blackfoot tradition at the time of having several wives and several children; he died on Feb 24, 1897 in Calgary.

== Career as a runner ==
By 1880, Deerfoot-Bad Meat had become an exceptional [[Long-distance running|long-distance runner]] working as a messenger for the [[Blackfoot Confederacy]] running between camps in [[Alberta]], [[Saskatchewan]] and [[Montana]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ashfm.ca/hall-of-fame-honoured-members/browse/achievement-award/deerfoot|title=Alberta Sports Hall of Fame and Museum|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

Deerfoot-Bad Meat first began running in minor local races when he was discovered by a Calgary gambling group called The Syndicate. The group was interested in finding local runners who could compete with continental champions for gambling money. Around the same time the indoor track "Star-Rink" was being built in Calgary which would serve as a venue for these championship foot-races. In 1883, in one of his first professional races, Deerfoot-Bad Meat defeated professional runner James Green and Blackfoot runner Little Plume in a four-day endurance race. In 16 hours, he completed 84 miles and 6 laps. Following this, Api-kai-ees was officially given the professional name Deerfoot, after the original [[Seneca people|Seneca]] runner [[Deerfoot|Deerfoot-Red Jacket]].

Deerfoot-Bad Meat continued to run successfully in many more local races in the Calgary area and beyond defeating challengers from as far away as Europe. In 1886 he won the prestigious [[Canada Day|Dominion Day]] one-mile race, coming within a second of breaking the world record for that distance.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/api_kai_ees_12E.html|title=API-KAI-EES|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

Later that autumn, in order to showcase Canadian talent to the world, multiple gambling groups decided to organize a major ten-mile race in Calgary. Deerfoot-Bad Meat was entered to run against the favourite J.W. Strokes of [[Birmingham]], [[England]] and George Irvine of [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/news/Deerfoot+Revenge/6752087/story.html|title="Deerfoots Revenge"  The Calgary Herald|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>  In what was considered the race of the decade, Deerfoot-Bad Meat overwhelmingly defeated Stokes and Irvine, beating the Englishman by a full lap. Not happy with what the Europeans considered a "humilliating" defeat, the handlers of the British runner claimed a miscount of laps and the race was invalidated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/news/Deerfoot+Revenge/6752087/story.html|title="Deerfoot's Revenge"  The Calgary Herald|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/en/bio/api_kai_ees_12E.html|title=Dictionary of Canadian Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The organizers rescheduled a new race for several days later. Nevertheless, being already suspicious of the British team, Deerfoot-Bad Meat stepped onto the race track only after giving Stokes a six lap head-start in order to dispel any possibility of another miscount. Deerfoot nevertheless passed the Birmingham racer and finished the ten miles in 54 minutes 30 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/wayward-west-episode-1-deerfoot-api-kai-ees-1.4183603|title="How the legend of Deerfoot rallied Calgary — and ruined the man"  - CBC|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://passherald.ca/archives/170719/index6.htm|title="Deerfoot - The Original Sinister 7 Runner" - Crowsnest Pass Herald|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

== Later career and death ==
Disillusioned and disappointed with the corruption involving the gambling group The Syndicate, Deerfoot parted ways with his team in 1886 and began running as an independent with mixed success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ashfm.ca/hall-of-fame-honoured-members/browse/achievement-award/deerfoot|title=Api-Kai-ees Deerfoot*|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> Deerfoot died in 1897 of [[tuberculosis]] and is buried in an unmarked grave in Calgary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/news/Deerfoot+Revenge/6752087/story.html|title=Deerfoot's Revenge|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=":0" />

In 1974 the City of [[Calgary]] renamed a major [[Controlled-access highway|freeway]], [[Deerfoot Trail]], as well as an industrial centre and shopping venue ([[Deerfoot City]]) in his honour.<ref name="auto"/>

